    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>Some IDEs will copy the signature of the abstract/interface method when inserting an implementing method in a sub class.</p>\n\n<p>I don't believe it makes any difference to the compiler.</p>\n\n<p>EDIT: While I believe this was true in the past, I don't think current IDEs do this any more.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 263812,
      "reputation" : 7432,
      "user_id" : 549641,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/c97f3ebc820da8f94f4495a7ba8dc9b6?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "jmg",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/549641/jmg"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 19,
    "last_activity_date" : 1300723429,
    "creation_date" : 1300723429,
    "answer_id" : 5380288,
    "question_id" : 5380177,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 2.5",
    "body" : "<p>Final annotations of method parameters are always only relevant to the method implementation never to the caller. Therefore, there is no real reason to use them in interface method signatures. Unless you want to follow the same consistent coding standard, which requires final method parameters, in all method signatures. Then it is nice to be able to do so.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 5460,
      "reputation" : 6382,
      "user_id" : 8792,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/94670849979d5cfa60a2f0a1138c2dbf?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "Peter",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/8792/peter"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 2,
    "last_activity_date" : 1300723505,
    "creation_date" : 1300723505,
    "answer_id" : 5380305,
    "question_id" : 5380177,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 2.5",
    "body" : "<p>I believe it may be a superfluous detail, as whether it's final or not is an implementation detail.</p>\n\n<p>(Sort of like declaring methods/members in an interface as public.)</p>\n"
  }, {
